 www.vitac.com

00:41.375 --> 00:44.376
CAPTIONS PAID FOR BY
DISCOVERY COMMUNICATIONS

00:44.378 --> 00:47.446
♪

00:47.448 --> 00:52.284
THE UNITED STATES IS RENOWNED
FOR ITS NAVAL MIGHT.

00:52.286 --> 00:53.886
IT HAS SOME OF THE FASTEST

00:53.888 --> 00:57.222
AND MOST HEAVILY-ARMED SHIPS
ON THE PLANET.

00:57.224 --> 01:01.660
BUT PATROLLING THE 139 MILLION
SQUARE-MILES OF OCEANS

01:01.662 --> 01:04.663
REQUIRES MORE.

01:04.665 --> 01:09.168
ITS AIRBORNE UNITS ARE VITAL
TO THE NAVY'S SUCCESS.

01:09.170 --> 01:12.037
AND BASING AN AIR FORCE AT SEA

01:12.039 --> 01:14.640
PRESENTS A UNIQUE
ENGINEERING CHALLENGE

01:14.642 --> 01:15.674
FOR PEOPLE LIKE

01:15.676 --> 01:17.709
CHIEF PETTY OFFICER
JEREMY STOECKLEIN

01:17.711 --> 01:19.278
AND HIS COLLEAGUES.

01:19.280 --> 01:20.612
Stoecklein: THOSE WATERS
NEED TO BE PATROLLED,

01:20.614 --> 01:23.182
NEED TO BE PROTECTED
FOR AMERICAN INTERESTS.

01:23.184 --> 01:24.616
THE FOREFRONT OF MILITARY MIGHT

01:24.618 --> 01:27.119
HAS REALLY BECOME
NAVAL AVIATION,

01:27.121 --> 01:28.620
AND IT'S VERY, VERY IMPORTANT

01:28.622 --> 01:31.457
TO TRANSFER THAT POWER
ANYWHERE IN THE WORLD.

01:31.459 --> 01:34.726
Narrator: THE U.S. NAVY
REQUIRES A NEW BREED OF SHIP

01:34.728 --> 01:38.931
CAPABLE OF TRANSPORTING
MORE PLANES THAN EVER BEFORE.

01:38.933 --> 01:40.799
AS WE MOVE INTO
THE 21st CENTURY,

01:40.801 --> 01:42.167
THERE BECOMES A NEW NEED --

01:42.169 --> 01:44.036
A NEW NEED FOR TECHNOLOGY,

01:44.038 --> 01:46.271
A NEW WAY TO COMBAT
THE FORCES AROUND THE WORLD,

01:46.273 --> 01:47.873
AND TO HELP OUT
WITH HUMANITARIAN EFFORTS

01:47.875 --> 01:49.908
AROUND THE WORLD.

01:49.910 --> 01:51.677
THE UNITED STATES NAVY
NEEDS SOMETHING

01:51.679 --> 01:54.346
BRAND NEW IN TECHNOLOGY
TO HELP THOSE AIDS.

01:54.348 --> 01:56.415
♪

01:56.417 --> 01:58.217
Narrator: THE SOLUTION...

01:58.219 --> 02:01.320
♪

02:01.322 --> 02:04.289
...THE FORD-CLASS
AIRCRAFT CARRIER.

02:04.291 --> 02:09.294
♪

02:09.296 --> 02:12.064
Butler: FORD-CLASS CARRIER IS
THE LARGEST WARSHIP EVER BUILT.

02:12.066 --> 02:13.799
IT'S ABOUT 1,100 FEET LONG,

02:13.801 --> 02:16.335
WEIGHTS ABOUT 100,000 TONS,

02:16.337 --> 02:19.505
IT'S ABOUT 24 STORIES TALL.

02:19.507 --> 02:21.540
Narrator: ITS SCALE
IS UNHEARD OF.

02:21.542 --> 02:24.910
IT'S 35-KNOT TOP SPEED
MAKES IT POUND-FOR-POUND

02:24.912 --> 02:28.046
THE FASTEST CARRIER EVER BUILT,

02:28.048 --> 02:31.183
AND IT'S ON THE BRINK
OF MAKING HISTORY.

02:31.185 --> 02:34.286
THE FIRST OF THE COLOSSAL CLASS,
<i> THE GERALD R. FORD,</i>

02:34.288 --> 02:37.789
HAS JUST BEEN DELIVERED
TO THE U.S. NAVY

02:37.791 --> 02:39.758
AND IS UNDERGOING
VITAL SEA TRIALS

02:39.760 --> 02:42.694
TO FIND OUT
WHAT IT'S CAPABLE OF.

02:42.696 --> 02:45.597
THIS SHIP CAN CARRY AIRCRAFT
AND TECHNOLOGIES

02:45.599 --> 02:46.832
THAT ARE OUT TODAY,

02:46.834 --> 02:50.002
AS WELL AS THAT WE HAVEN'T
EVEN DREAMT OF YET.

02:50.004 --> 02:54.072
THIS IS THE MOST IMPRESSIVE SHIP
I'VE EVER SERVED ABOARD.

02:54.074 --> 02:56.008
♪

02:56.010 --> 02:58.544
Narrator: IN DRY DOCK
IN NEWPORT NEWS, VIRGINIA,

02:58.546 --> 03:00.679
GEOFF HUMMEL
AND A TEAM OF ENGINEERS

03:00.681 --> 03:01.780
ARE BUILDING THE SECOND

03:01.782 --> 03:05.284
OF THIS 10-STRONG FLEET
OF CARRIERS --

03:05.286 --> 03:08.720
<i> THE JOHN F. KENNEDY.</i>

03:08.722 --> 03:10.656
Hummel: WE'VE BEEN WORKING ON IT
FOR ABOUT THREE YEARS,

03:10.658 --> 03:13.058
AND WE GOT ABOUT ANOTHER YEAR
AND A HALF IN THE DRY DOCK,

03:13.060 --> 03:15.127
AND THEN AFTER THAT, WE'LL SPEND
ABOUT TWO YEARS OF TESTING IT

03:15.129 --> 03:17.529
BEFORE WE DELIVER IT.

03:17.531 --> 03:19.264
Narrator: MIKE BUTLER
HEADS UP CONSTRUCTION

03:19.266 --> 03:22.801
OF THESE TRAILBLAZING SHIPS.

03:22.803 --> 03:25.704
WELL, AN AIRCRAFT CARRIER HAS
TO SATISFY TWO MAJOR ROLES --

03:25.706 --> 03:27.406
ONE IS A HUMANITARIAN ROLE,

03:27.408 --> 03:30.242
AND ONE IS A DEFENSIVE
OR OFFENSIVE MILITARY ROLE.

03:30.244 --> 03:32.744
THIS SHIP DOES BOTH
AND DOES IT VERY WELL.

03:32.746 --> 03:36.882
♪

03:36.884 --> 03:39.384
Narrator: THE LARGEST WARSHIP
EVER BUILT,

03:39.386 --> 03:41.887
THE FORD-CLASS CARRIER
IS ALMOST AS LONG

03:41.889 --> 03:44.389
AS THE EMPIRE STATE BUILDING
IS TALL.

03:44.391 --> 03:47.826
35 AIRCRAFT ARE STORED
IN A GIANT HANGAR.

03:47.828 --> 03:50.963
THREE SUPER-SIZED ELEVATORS
DELIVER THE PLANES

03:50.965 --> 03:55.434
TO AN 1,100-FOOT-LONG
FLIGHT DECK.

03:55.436 --> 03:58.904
EQUIPPED WITH AN ELECTROMAGNETIC
CATAPULT SYSTEM

03:58.906 --> 04:02.641
CAPABLE OF LAUNCHING PLANES
FASTER THAN EVER BEFORE.

04:02.643 --> 04:06.478
♪

04:06.480 --> 04:10.048
THE AMOUNT OF TECHNOLOGY THAT'S
BEEN INFUSED INTO THIS SHIP

04:10.050 --> 04:11.817
IS GONNA PUT THE NAVY
IN A POSITION

04:11.819 --> 04:14.353
TO FIGHT THE WARS
OF THE 21st CENTURY.

04:14.355 --> 04:17.589
IT'S GONNA BE THE MOST CAPABLE
SHIP OUT THERE IN THE FLEET.

04:17.591 --> 04:20.025
[ ENGINE ROARS ]

04:20.027 --> 04:22.861
Narrator: BUT CREATING THE
WORLD'S LARGEST MOBILE AIR BASE

04:22.863 --> 04:25.397
POSES MANY CHALLENGES.

04:25.399 --> 04:28.600
HOW DO YOU POWER
A 110,000 TON VESSEL

04:28.602 --> 04:31.603
WITH 4,500 CREW MEMBERS?

04:31.605 --> 04:33.171
Stoecklein: WHAT WE DO IS,
LIVE EVERYDAY LIVES.

04:33.173 --> 04:34.406
SO, WASHING LAUNDRY,

04:34.408 --> 04:36.241
SERVING 20,000 MEALS A DAY.

04:36.243 --> 04:39.077
SO, IT'S LIKE POWERING,
ESSENTIALLY, A SMALL CITY.

04:39.079 --> 04:41.380
Narrator: HOW IS IT POSSIBLE
TO GET JETS AIRBORNE

04:41.382 --> 04:44.249
IN JUST A FRACTION
OF A NORMAL RUNWAY?

04:44.251 --> 04:47.452
THE GREATEST CHALLENGE IS
TO BE ABLE TO GET THE AIRCRAFT

04:47.454 --> 04:50.889
TO THE SPEED THAT IT NEEDS
IN ORDER TO TAKE OFF.

04:50.891 --> 04:54.359
Narrator: AND HOW CAN YOU
BRING THEM HOME SAFELY?

04:54.361 --> 04:58.096
LANDING ON A CARRIER
REQUIRES AN EXTERNAL MEANS

04:58.098 --> 05:01.566
OF STOPPING THE AIRCRAFT.

05:01.568 --> 05:05.504
Narrator: BUT THE ENGINEERS FACE
AN EVEN BIGGER PROBLEM.

05:05.506 --> 05:06.872
♪

05:06.874 --> 05:09.041
THE FORD CLASS HOLDS MORE PLANES

05:09.043 --> 05:11.510
THAN ANY CARRIER BEFORE IT.

05:11.512 --> 05:13.278
THEY MUST BE ABLE
TO LAUNCH AND RECOVER

05:13.280 --> 05:16.248
AN ASTONISHING
200 MISSIONS A DAY.

05:16.250 --> 05:19.551
SO, HOW DO YOU ACHIEVE THAT
ON A SHIP?

05:19.553 --> 05:23.555
ENGINEER MARCO ESTRADA
IS FACING THAT CHALLENGE.

05:23.557 --> 05:25.791
Estrada: TYPICALLY,
AN AIRCRAFT CARRIER

05:25.793 --> 05:30.896
OF THE FORD CLASS WILL HOLD
APPROXIMATELY 78, 79 AIRCRAFT.

05:30.898 --> 05:33.298
THE JOB OF MANAGING
THE FLIGHT DECK

05:33.300 --> 05:35.334
IS AN ORGANIZED CHAOS.

05:35.336 --> 05:37.035
WE HAVE LAUNCHES,
YOU GOT RECOVERIES,

05:37.037 --> 05:38.003
YOU GOT FUELING,

05:38.005 --> 05:40.138
YOU GOT WEAPONS
AT THE SAME TIME.

05:40.140 --> 05:43.141
SO, IT'S A VERY
CHALLENGING OPERATION.

05:43.143 --> 05:45.477
Narrator: TO ACHIEVE THEIR
UNPRECEDENTED MISSION RATE,

05:45.479 --> 05:47.679
SOME AIRCRAFT
MUST BE ABLE TO LAND

05:47.681 --> 05:51.149
AT THE SAME TIME
THAT OTHERS ARE TAKING OFF.

05:51.151 --> 05:53.518
IT'S AN IMPOSSIBLE PROBLEM
THAT WAS FACED

05:53.520 --> 05:56.054
BY THE INNOVATORS OF THE PAST.

05:57.257 --> 05:58.957
[ CLOCK TICKING ]

06:01.362 --> 06:06.331
♪

06:06.333 --> 06:09.034
U.S. NAVY PILOT
LIEUTENANT LESLIE GARCIA

06:09.036 --> 06:11.136
IS A FAST JET SPECIALIST,

06:11.138 --> 06:12.871
WELL AWARE OF THE HUGE PROBLEMS

06:12.873 --> 06:16.475
OF LAUNCHING AND LANDING
ON AN AIRCRAFT CARRIER.

06:16.477 --> 06:20.145
IT IS NOT UNCOMMON TO HAVE
OVER 20 AIRCRAFT LAUNCH

06:20.147 --> 06:23.081
RIGHT BEFORE 20 AIRCRAFT
ARE RECOVERING

06:23.083 --> 06:25.450
DURING THE SAME OPEN-DECK TIME.

06:27.221 --> 06:28.820
♪

06:28.822 --> 06:31.123
Narrator: TO SIMULATE THE
STRAIGHT DECK'S LIMITATIONS,

06:31.125 --> 06:33.458
LIEUTENANT GARCIA IS
HANDING OVER THE FLYING

06:33.460 --> 06:37.229
TO A MODEL PLANE CLUB.

06:37.231 --> 06:39.231
Garcia: SO, RIGHT NOW, WE'RE
PUTTING DOWN THE CENTER LINE

06:39.233 --> 06:40.866
OF THE STRAIGHT DECK CARRIER.

06:40.868 --> 06:42.768
I DIDN'T KNOW I WAS
GONNA GET A WORKOUT

06:42.770 --> 06:46.004
WHILE I WAS OUT HERE, TOO.

06:46.006 --> 06:47.773
Narrator: THE HISTORIC
STRAIGHT-DECK DESIGN

06:47.775 --> 06:49.341
IS READY FOR TAKEOFF,

06:49.343 --> 06:51.510
BUT HOW WILL IT COPE?

06:51.512 --> 06:54.179
THEY'RE GONNA GO AIRBORNE,
EXECUTE THEIR MISSION,

06:54.181 --> 06:56.515
AND THEN LOOK
TO COME IN AND LAND.

06:56.517 --> 06:59.951
♪

06:59.953 --> 07:01.887
Narrator: AS THE MISSION
GATHERS PACE,

07:01.889 --> 07:05.524
LANDING SIMULTANEOUSLY
IS IMPOSSIBLE.

07:05.526 --> 07:07.459
Garcia: NOW WE'VE GOT
THE NEXT CYCLE OF PILOTS

07:07.461 --> 07:09.394
GETTING READY TO TAKE OFF
WHILE THE FIRST CYCLE

07:09.396 --> 07:10.929
THAT WE LAUNCHED
ARE STILL AIRBORNE

07:10.931 --> 07:13.398
AND WAITING FOR THE OPPORTUNITY
TO COME LAND.

07:13.400 --> 07:14.699
SO, AS YOU CAN SEE,

07:14.701 --> 07:18.503
THEY'RE, BASICALLY,
FOULING THE WHOLE FLIGHT DECK.

07:18.505 --> 07:20.872
IT'S A VERY INEFFICIENT PROCESS.

07:22.576 --> 07:24.443
♪

07:24.445 --> 07:26.044
Narrator: BUT IN THE 1950s,

07:26.046 --> 07:29.381
AIRCRAFT-CARRIER DESIGN
WAS TURNED ON ITS HEAD.

07:29.383 --> 07:32.984
♪

07:32.986 --> 07:35.420
NOW A FLOATING MUSEUM
IN SAN DIEGO,

07:35.422 --> 07:36.555
THE<i> U.S.S. MIDWAY</i>

07:36.557 --> 07:38.924
WAS ONE OF THE FIRST
AMERICAN CARRIERS

07:38.926 --> 07:41.726
TO BE FITTED WITH
A GAME-CHANGING SOLUTION --

07:41.728 --> 07:43.395
THE ANGLED DECK.

07:43.397 --> 07:47.399
♪

07:47.401 --> 07:49.100
IT WAS THE BRAINCHILD OF BRITISH

07:49.102 --> 07:51.169
ROYAL NAVY CAPTAIN
DENNIS CAMBELL

07:51.171 --> 07:54.005
AND ENGINEER LEWIS BODDINGTON.

07:54.007 --> 07:55.540
♪

07:55.542 --> 07:58.076
THEY SUPPLEMENTED
THE TRADITIONAL STRAIGHT DECK

07:58.078 --> 08:00.445
WITH A SECOND RUNWAY.

08:00.447 --> 08:05.550
THE PLANE'S LANDING AREA WAS NOW
SEPARATED AT THE SHIP'S WAIST

08:05.552 --> 08:08.053
WHILE LAUNCH CATAPULTS
WERE SAFELY POSITIONED

08:08.055 --> 08:11.122
AT THE FRONT OF THE SHIP.

08:11.124 --> 08:12.491
Garcia: WHEN THIS WAS
A STRAIGHT DECK,

08:12.493 --> 08:15.060
YOU WOULD, BASICALLY,
JUST SEE ONE LANDING AREA

08:15.062 --> 08:16.661
STRAIGHT UP AND DOWN THE SHIP,

08:16.663 --> 08:18.530
WITH TAXIING
AND LAUNCHING AIRCRAFT

08:18.532 --> 08:19.998
TOWARDS THE BOW OF THE SHIP,

08:20.000 --> 08:21.967
LANDING AIRCRAFT
TOWARDS THE BACK.

08:21.969 --> 08:23.368
REALLY, THE GAME WAS CHANGED

08:23.370 --> 08:25.437
WHEN WE WENT OVER
TO THE ANGLED FLIGHT DECK.

08:25.439 --> 08:27.005
IT BECAME SO MUCH
MORE EFFICIENT,

08:27.007 --> 08:30.008
AND, MORE IMPORTANTLY,
SO MUCH SAFER.

08:30.010 --> 08:31.977
Narrator: THE<i> MIDWAY'S</i>
REMARKABLE REFIT

08:31.979 --> 08:36.815
ALLOWED HER PLANES TO TAKE OFF
AND LAND AT THE SAME TIME.

08:36.817 --> 08:38.950
Garcia: THE LANDING AIRCRAFT
ARE GONNA BE OFFSET

08:38.952 --> 08:40.952
SO THAT IF THEY NEED
TO TAKE BACK OFF,

08:40.954 --> 08:42.454
IF THEY MISSED A WIRE,

08:42.456 --> 08:44.956
THEY WILL HAVE THE ANGLED DECK

08:44.958 --> 08:46.591
THAT IS GOING TO KEEP THEM AWAY

08:46.593 --> 08:49.928
FROM THE LAUNCHING AIRCRAFT THAT
ARE LAUNCHING STRAIGHT AHEAD.

08:49.930 --> 08:51.429
[ BIRD WHISTLES ]

08:51.431 --> 08:53.598
♪

08:53.600 --> 08:55.433
Narrator: SO, WILL
ADDING AN ANGLED DECK

08:55.435 --> 08:57.969
BRING SOME ORDER
TO TODAY'S MISSION?

08:57.971 --> 09:03.074
♪

09:03.076 --> 09:05.944
Garcia: AS YOU CAN SEE,
WE'VE GOT ONE TAKING OFF.

09:05.946 --> 09:08.513
♪

09:08.515 --> 09:10.849
HE'S GONNA COME AROUND AND
START EXECUTING TOUCH-AND-GOES

09:10.851 --> 09:13.351
WHILE WE LAUNCH
THE OTHER AIRCRAFT.

09:13.353 --> 09:14.553
Narrator: AS ON THE<i> MIDWAY,</i>

09:14.555 --> 09:16.121
CAMBELL AND BODDINGTON'S
ADDITION

09:16.123 --> 09:19.991
TRANSFORMS THIS AIRSTRIP
INTO A WELL-OILED MACHINE.

09:19.993 --> 09:22.561
Garcia: HE'S APPROACHING
ON HIS LANDING.

09:22.563 --> 09:24.930
LET'S GO AHEAD
AND LAUNCH THE SECOND.

09:24.932 --> 09:27.299
AND YOU CAN SEE THAT
THOSE TWO FLIGHT PATHS

09:27.301 --> 09:30.235
ARE NATURALLY DECONFLICTED
BECAUSE OF THE ANGLE

09:30.237 --> 09:32.771
THAT LANDING AIRCRAFT
IS COMING IN ON.

09:32.773 --> 09:34.940
AND WE'RE BASICALLY GETTING
TWO LANDING STRIPS

09:34.942 --> 09:36.474
FOR THE PRICE OF ONE.

09:36.476 --> 09:40.679
♪

09:42.382 --> 09:43.915
[ CLOCK TICKING ]

09:46.253 --> 09:49.254
♪

09:49.256 --> 09:51.723
Narrator: THE U.S. NAVY'S
ULTRA-MODERN FORD CLASS

09:51.725 --> 09:54.159
IS ALSO EQUIPPED
WITH AN ANGLED DECK.

09:54.161 --> 09:58.396
♪

09:58.398 --> 10:02.601
BUT WHEREAS<i> MIDWAY</i> LAUNCHED
JUST 89 SORTIES A DAY,

10:02.603 --> 10:05.870
THE FORD CLASS
CAN COMPLETE OVER 200.

10:05.872 --> 10:07.806
♪

10:07.808 --> 10:09.240
WHEN YOU LOOK AT THE FLIGHT DECK
AS A WHOLE,

10:09.242 --> 10:10.709
4-1/2 ACRES SEEMS LARGE,

10:10.711 --> 10:13.178
BUT AS YOU ADD
50 FIGHTER AIRCRAFT

10:13.180 --> 10:15.580
AND AROUND 100 TO 150 PERSONNEL
AT ALL TIMES

10:15.582 --> 10:16.848
PERFORMING THEIR VARIOUS TASKS,

10:16.850 --> 10:19.284
IT GETS VERY, VERY SMALL
VERY QUICKLY.

10:19.286 --> 10:22.687
THE BALLET OF US DOING OUR JOB
THEY CALL "CONTROLLED CHAOS,"

10:22.689 --> 10:23.922
AND THAT'S REALLY WHAT IT IS.

10:23.924 --> 10:26.157
400 YARDS!

10:26.159 --> 10:28.026
Narrator: THE CAMBELL-
AND-BODDINGTON-INSPIRED

10:28.028 --> 10:30.462
ANGLED FLIGHT DECK
ENABLES THE FORD CLASS

10:30.464 --> 10:33.365
TO COMPLETE 25% MORE
SORTIES A DAY

10:33.367 --> 10:36.301
THAN THE U.S. NAVY'S
PREVIOUS CARRIER CLASS.

10:36.303 --> 10:38.269
Stoecklein: THE ANGLED
FLIGHT DECK IS A MAJOR FEAT

10:38.271 --> 10:39.971
IN ENGINEERING IN ITSELF.

10:39.973 --> 10:42.307
WITH THAT ANGLED FLIGHT DECK,
WE HAVE A LIVING AIRPORT

10:42.309 --> 10:44.376
THAT IS RECEIVING AIRCRAFT
AT THE SAME TIME

10:44.378 --> 10:48.446
IT IS LAUNCHING AIRCRAFT,
SIMULTANEOUSLY.

10:48.448 --> 10:51.182
Narrator: WITH THE SECOND
IN CLASS, THE<i> JOHN F. KENNEDY,</i>

10:51.184 --> 10:53.852
UNDER CONSTRUCTION,
IT'S UP TO ENGINEER MARCO

10:53.854 --> 10:58.089
TO DELIVER THE FORD CLASS'S
NEXT AWESOME ANGLED DECK.

10:58.091 --> 11:00.425
Estrada: CURRENTLY, WE ARE
AT THE 01 LEVEL OF THE SHIP.

11:00.427 --> 11:03.328
SO, THERE IS GONNA BE
A COUPLE MORE LEVELS GOING UP

11:03.330 --> 11:04.863
WHERE THE FLIGHT DECK'S
GOING TO BE.

11:04.865 --> 11:07.399
SO, CURRENTLY, WE'RE A LITTLE
LOWER THAN THE FLIGHT DECK.

11:07.401 --> 11:09.134
BUT ONCE THE FLIGHT DECK
IS INSTALLED,

11:09.136 --> 11:11.636
WE SHOULD SEE THE ANGLED DECK
IN THIS DIRECTION,

11:11.638 --> 11:14.472
THE ISLAND STRUCTURE SHOULD
BE IN THAT DIRECTION.

11:14.474 --> 11:17.175
Narrator: AND THAT, IN ITSELF,
IS A MAJOR INNOVATION.

11:17.177 --> 11:19.711
SO, JUST HOW DID MOVING
THE ISLAND IN RELATION

11:19.713 --> 11:21.246
TO THE REST OF THE FLIGHT DECK

11:21.248 --> 11:24.582
CHANGE AIRCRAFT-CARRIER
DESIGN FOREVER?

11:24.584 --> 11:27.752
♪

11:36.430 --> 11:40.965
♪

11:40.967 --> 11:44.235
Narrator: THE CUTTING EDGE
FORD-CLASS AIRCRAFT CARRIER,

11:44.237 --> 11:47.639
A STUDY IN NAVAL INNOVATION
AND A DRAMATIC IMPROVEMENT

11:47.641 --> 11:50.442
ON FLIGHT-DECK EFFICIENCY
AND SAFETY.

11:50.444 --> 11:52.177
IT DIFFERS FROM ITS PREDECESSORS

11:52.179 --> 11:53.878
IN A NUMBER OF WAYS.

11:55.582 --> 11:57.916
FOR EXAMPLE,
THE POSITION OF THE ISLAND

11:57.918 --> 12:00.785
IS RADICALLY DIFFERENT
FROM ALL PREVIOUS DESIGNS

12:00.787 --> 12:03.354
OF U.S. AIRCRAFT CARRIERS.

12:03.356 --> 12:05.290
THIS IS ONE OF THE KEYS
TO THE CLASS'S

12:05.292 --> 12:07.492
EXTRAORDINARY CAPACITY TO LAUNCH

12:07.494 --> 12:10.428
AND RECOVER AIRCRAFT
AT THE SAME TIME.

12:10.430 --> 12:12.430
♪

12:12.432 --> 12:14.833
Estrada: ON FORD CLASS,
THE ISLAND STRUCTURE

12:14.835 --> 12:16.634
WAS MOVED FROM THIS AREA

12:16.636 --> 12:19.204
TO AN AREA CLOSER
TO THE STERN OF THE SHIP.

12:19.206 --> 12:22.574
THAT ALLOWS MORE OF THE PARKING
OF THE AIRCRAFT FORWARD

12:22.576 --> 12:24.042
OF THE ISLAND STRUCTURE,

12:24.044 --> 12:26.111
WHICH ALLOWS THE NAVY OPERATORS

12:26.113 --> 12:28.046
TO TURN AROUND
THE AIRCRAFT FASTER.

12:28.048 --> 12:31.149
FUEL, SERVICE, WEAPONS LOADING,

12:31.151 --> 12:33.852
IN TURN, GENERATES MORE SORTIES.

12:33.854 --> 12:36.855
♪

12:38.959 --> 12:42.560
AT THIS POINT IN TIME,
THIS AIRCRAFT CARRIER DESIGN

12:42.562 --> 12:45.897
IS THE PINNACLE
OF FLIGHT OPERATIONS SUPPORT

12:45.899 --> 12:49.134
FOR THE U.S. NAVY.

12:49.136 --> 12:52.070
Narrator: THE RELOCATED ISLAND
ALSO HAS A SMALLER FOOTPRINT

12:52.072 --> 12:53.371
THAN ITS PREDECESSORS,

12:53.373 --> 12:56.808
CREATING AN EXTRA USABLE
DECK SPACE.

12:56.810 --> 12:58.109
BENEATH THE RUNWAYS,

12:58.111 --> 13:00.512
AIRCRAFT ARE STORED
IN A GIANT HANGAR,

13:00.514 --> 13:01.913
DELIVERED TO THE FLIGHT DECK

13:01.915 --> 13:05.750
BY 82-FOOT-LONG
ELECTROMECHANICAL ELEVATORS.

13:05.752 --> 13:10.655
♪

13:10.657 --> 13:12.791
POSITIONED ON THE SIDES
OF THE SHIP,

13:12.793 --> 13:14.292
ANY CRAFT CAN BE MANEUVERED

13:14.294 --> 13:17.328
WITHOUT DISRUPTING LAUNCH
OR RECOVERY.

13:19.699 --> 13:22.033
Stoecklein: WHAT YOU'RE LOOKING
AT IS WHAT WE CALL ACE 3,

13:22.035 --> 13:24.369
OR AIRCRAFT ELEVATOR NUMBER 3,

13:24.371 --> 13:26.337
WHICH IS RIGHT HERE
ON THE PORT SIDE OF THE SHIP.

13:26.339 --> 13:28.673
AND THE ELEVATOR IS UP
RIGHT NOW, AS YOU CAN SEE,

13:28.675 --> 13:32.210
BUT AS YOU LOOK ON THESE SLOTS,
THIS IS WHAT ACTUALLY SLIDES

13:32.212 --> 13:34.312
OUR AIRCRAFT ELEVATORS DOWN
TO THE HANGAR BAY,

13:34.314 --> 13:36.915
AND HOW WE MOVE
OUR AIRCRAFT IN AND OUT

13:36.917 --> 13:38.683
FOR MAINTENANCE AND OPERATIONS

13:38.685 --> 13:40.051
AND THEN MOVE IT BACK UP
TO THE FLIGHT DECK

13:40.053 --> 13:41.820
AND TAXI THEM OFF.

13:41.822 --> 13:43.988
Narrator: THE FORD CLASS
IS UNDOUBTEDLY TAKING

13:43.990 --> 13:47.458
AIRCRAFT DEPLOYMENT
TO A WHOLE NEW LEVEL.

13:47.460 --> 13:50.929
BUT THE ENGINEERS FACE
ANOTHER ALMIGHTY PROBLEM --

13:50.931 --> 13:53.097
POWERING THIS GIANT CARRIER,

13:53.099 --> 13:55.099
AND IT<i> IS</i> GIANT.

13:55.101 --> 13:56.935
♪

13:56.937 --> 13:58.903
Stoecklein: THE AIRCRAFT CARRIER
IS A MOVING BASE.

13:58.905 --> 14:00.104
IT IS A MOVING CITY.

14:00.106 --> 14:02.907
SO, WE HAVE A MOBILE CITY,
A MOBILE AIRSTRIP,

14:02.909 --> 14:05.076
WITH ALL OF THE CAPABILITIES
OF ANY AIRFIELD,

14:05.078 --> 14:07.412
AND IT CAN BE MOVED
ANYWHERE IN THE WORLD.

14:07.414 --> 14:09.314
♪

14:09.316 --> 14:11.683
Narrator: AS TALL
AS A GIANT SEQUOIA,

14:11.685 --> 14:14.152
LONGER THAN 60 NEW YORK CABS,

14:14.154 --> 14:17.355
AND ALMOST THE WIDTH
OF AN AIRBUS A380,

14:17.357 --> 14:22.694
IT CAN HOLD UP TO 75 AIRCRAFT
AND ACCOMMODATE 4,500 CREW.

14:22.696 --> 14:27.165
♪

14:27.167 --> 14:30.268
IN THE DRY DOCK, THE SECOND
OF THIS BRAND-NEW CLASS,

14:30.270 --> 14:34.205
THE<i> JOHN F. KENNEDY,</i>
IS CURRENTLY BEING ASSEMBLED.

14:34.207 --> 14:36.174
CONSTRUCTION DIRECTOR
GEOFF HUMMEL

14:36.176 --> 14:39.210
IS SUPERVISING PART
OF THE MAMMOTH BUILD.

14:40.680 --> 14:42.313
Hummel: WHEN WE'RE DONE

14:42.315 --> 14:43.448
BUILDING HER,
WE'LL DELIVER A SHIP

14:43.450 --> 14:46.217
OF A LITTLE OVER 80,000 TONS
OF DISPLACEMENT.

14:46.219 --> 14:49.053
WHEN THE NAVY ACTUALLY LOADS
IT UP WITH CREW AND PLANES

14:49.055 --> 14:52.924
AND SUPPLIES, IT'LL BE CLOSE
TO 100,000 TONS GOING TO SEA.

14:52.926 --> 14:55.927
Narrator: IT WILL TAKE MORE
THAN 3.9 MILLION POUNDS

14:55.929 --> 14:58.630
OF WELDED METAL
TO COMPLETE THIS SHIP.

14:58.632 --> 15:00.164
CONSTRUCTION ON THIS SCALE

15:00.166 --> 15:03.434
CREATES HUGE
LOGISTICAL CHALLENGES.

15:03.436 --> 15:05.470
THE SOLUTION IS
TO BUILD THE<i> KENNEDY</i>

15:05.472 --> 15:07.572
IN A SERIES OF MASSIVE SECTIONS,

15:07.574 --> 15:10.208
KNOWN AS SUPER LIFTS.

15:10.210 --> 15:13.077
RIGHT BEHIND US IS WHAT WE CALL
THE LOWER BOW SUPER LIFT.

15:13.079 --> 15:16.114
IT'S ABOUT 60 FEET TALL,
A LITTLE OVER 100 FEET LONG.

15:16.116 --> 15:17.916
IT'S MADE UP OF SEVEN UNITS
THAT WERE BUILT

15:17.918 --> 15:20.084
IN OUR STEELS SHOPS,
BROUGHT OVER HERE,

15:20.086 --> 15:22.220
AND JOINED INTO
ONE GIANT SUPER LIFT.

15:22.222 --> 15:24.989
AND THEN IF YOU LOOK OVER,
JUST AFT OF IT,

15:24.991 --> 15:26.324
WHAT YOU'LL SEE
IS THE BEGINNINGS

15:26.326 --> 15:27.926
OF WHAT WE'LL CALL
THE UPPER BOW.

15:27.928 --> 15:29.761
YOU CAN ACTUALLY SEE
THE LEADING EDGE OF FLIGHT DECK

15:29.763 --> 15:31.663
THERE WITH THAT ROLLED SHAPE.

15:31.665 --> 15:34.365
THAT'S ACTUALLY GONNA BE
THE VERY BOW OF THE SHIP.

15:34.367 --> 15:36.901
Narrator: THESE MEGA-STRUCTURES
ARE ONLY POSSIBLE

15:36.903 --> 15:39.704
BECAUSE OF A STAGGERING PIECE
OF ENGINEERING...

15:39.706 --> 15:42.774
♪

15:42.776 --> 15:46.644
ONE OF THE LARGEST CRANES
IN THE WORLD.

15:46.646 --> 15:50.081
BEHIND ME HERE IS WHAT WE CALL
OUR 1,050-TON CRANE.

15:50.083 --> 15:53.284
OTHER PEOPLE AFFECTIONATELY
KNOW IT AS "BIG BLUE."

15:53.286 --> 15:56.621
THIS CRANE IS RATED
FOR 1,050 METRIC TONS.

15:56.623 --> 16:00.024
♪

16:00.026 --> 16:03.294
IT'S A VERY CAPABLE CRANE.

16:03.296 --> 16:06.698
THE CRANE HAS TWO RAILS RUNNING
WHAT WE CALL EAST AND WEST,

16:06.700 --> 16:08.499
TOWARDS AND AWAY FROM THE RIVER.

16:08.501 --> 16:11.669
IT SPANS ABOUT 540 FEET
BETWEEN THE RAILS,

16:11.671 --> 16:13.838
AND IT'S ABOUT 230 FEET TALL.

16:13.840 --> 16:16.307
♪

16:16.309 --> 16:19.577
Narrator:
WHEN YOU'RE MANEUVERING
1,100-TON STEEL SECTIONS,

16:19.579 --> 16:21.679
THERE'S NO ROOM FOR ERROR.

16:21.681 --> 16:26.150
BIG BLUE'S THREE HOISTS
ALLOW PINPOINT PRECISION.

16:26.152 --> 16:28.486
Hummel: WITH THIS CRANE,
YOU'RE ACTUALLY MAKING ONE MOVE

16:28.488 --> 16:30.688
WITH ALL THREE HOISTS
BEING SYNCHRONIZED.

16:30.690 --> 16:32.623
IT'S GOT SOME
PRETTY GOOD PRECISION,

16:32.625 --> 16:34.225
AS FAR AS HOW ACCURATELY

16:34.227 --> 16:36.060
WE CAN PLACE THE UNIT,
OR MOVE THE UNIT,

16:36.062 --> 16:38.396
TO GET IT WITHIN
AN INCH OR LESS.

16:38.398 --> 16:39.864
AND THEN WE CAN
ACTUALLY USE SOME JACKS

16:39.866 --> 16:42.500
TO POSITION THE UNIT
EXACTLY WHERE WE WANT IT.

16:42.502 --> 16:44.802
IT'S JUST COOL, MAN.
[ CHUCKLES ]

16:44.804 --> 16:46.404
♪

16:46.406 --> 16:49.273
Narrator: BUT ONCE AT SEA,
THE FORD CLASS'S SHEER SCALE

16:49.275 --> 16:52.777
POSES ANOTHER ENORMOUS PROBLEM.

16:52.779 --> 16:55.747
AS THEIR MISSIONS WILL LAST
FOR MONTHS AT A TIME,

16:55.749 --> 16:57.315
PROPELLING A SHIP OF THIS SIZE

16:57.317 --> 16:59.650
WITH TRADITIONAL THIRSTY
COMBUSTION ENGINES

16:59.652 --> 17:01.419
IS OUT OF THE QUESTION.

17:01.421 --> 17:03.955
♪

17:03.957 --> 17:06.657
NOT ONLY THAT,
THE POWER NEEDS TO SATISFY

17:06.659 --> 17:09.794
THE DEMANDS OF OVER 4,500 CREW.

17:09.796 --> 17:11.896
♪

17:11.898 --> 17:13.965
A NEW POWER SOURCE IS NEEDED.

17:13.967 --> 17:15.500
CAN THE INNOVATORS OF THE PAST

17:15.502 --> 17:17.668
SHED ANY LIGHT ON THE PROBLEM?

17:17.670 --> 17:20.638
♪

17:20.640 --> 17:24.142
[ CLOCK TICKING ]

17:24.144 --> 17:28.346
♪

17:28.348 --> 17:30.515
CARTAGENA IN SOUTHEAST SPAIN

17:30.517 --> 17:33.851
COULD HARBOR A SOLUTION
FOR THE FORD CLASS.

17:33.853 --> 17:36.020
♪

17:36.022 --> 17:38.790
FORMER SPANISH SUBMARINER
DIEGO QUEVEDO

17:38.792 --> 17:40.858
IS VISITING
THE HISTORIC NAVAL BASE

17:40.860 --> 17:43.828
OF A NATION
THAT ONCE RULED THE WAVES.

17:52.105 --> 17:54.105
♪

17:54.107 --> 17:55.506
BY THE 1800s,

17:55.508 --> 17:58.910
THE MIGHT OF THE SPANISH NAVY
MAY HAVE FADED AWAY,

17:58.912 --> 18:00.545
BUT IN 1888,

18:00.547 --> 18:04.282
A NEW BREED OF MARITIME
ENGINEERING SURFACED.

18:04.284 --> 18:10.621
♪

18:14.961 --> 18:16.327
THE WORLD'S FIRST

18:16.329 --> 18:19.597
FULLY-FUNCTIONING
MILITARY SUBMERSIBLE,

18:19.599 --> 18:23.968
THE 72-FOOT LONG PERAL
CHANGED THE FACE OF WARFARE.

18:35.815 --> 18:37.081
♪

18:37.083 --> 18:39.417
BUT THE SPANISH ENGINEERS
HAD THE SAME PROBLEM

18:39.419 --> 18:41.819
AS THE ONE FACING
THE FORD CLASS --

18:41.821 --> 18:43.354
HOW TO POWER THE PERAL

18:43.356 --> 18:46.357
ON LONG MISSIONS
THROUGH THE WORLD'S OCEANS.

18:55.702 --> 18:59.370
Narrator: HOWEVER, A COMBUSTION
ENGINE'S TOXIC FUMES

18:59.372 --> 19:02.807
WOULD BE DEADLY
IN THIS AIR-TIGHT STEEL TUBE.

19:12.152 --> 19:15.720
SO, HOW DID THE SPANISH NAVY
POWER THE PERAL,

19:15.722 --> 19:17.421
AND HOW CAN THE ANSWER HELP

19:17.423 --> 19:20.892
TO DRIVE THE GREATEST WARSHIP
EVER BUILT?

19:37.177 --> 19:40.311
Narrator: THE PERAL SUBMARINE
WAS THE FIRST SUBMERSIBLE VESSEL

19:40.313 --> 19:42.113
OF ITS KIND IN HISTORY,

19:42.115 --> 19:44.582
AND THE SPANISH NAVY
NEEDED A WAY TO POWER IT

19:44.584 --> 19:48.452
WITHOUT THE TOXIC FUMES OF
A TRADITIONAL COMBUSTION ENGINE.

19:50.190 --> 19:52.757
THE SUBMARINE'S DESIGNER,

19:52.759 --> 19:57.328
NAVAL ENGINEER ISAAC PERAL
HAD AN INGENIOUS ANSWER.

19:57.330 --> 20:00.131
TO CREATE SUSTAINABLE POWER
BENEATH THE WAVES,

20:00.133 --> 20:02.500
HE TURNED TO ELECTRICITY.

20:04.504 --> 20:06.537
AND TODAY, DIEGO QUEVEDO

20:06.539 --> 20:09.907
HAS SPECIAL ACCESS
TO THE HEART OF THE SOLUTION.

20:22.855 --> 20:26.557
THE PERAL WAS LINED
WITH 33 TONS' WORTH

20:26.559 --> 20:29.694
OF RECHARGEABLE
LEAD-ACID BATTERIES.

20:29.696 --> 20:31.062
THEIR FIRST JOB --

20:31.064 --> 20:34.131
TO PROPEL ITS SLEEK STRUCTURE
THROUGH THE DEPTHS.

20:51.584 --> 20:53.484
♪

20:53.486 --> 20:57.421
VIRTUALLY EVERY SYSTEM ON BOARD
WAS ALSO BATTERY-POWERED,

20:57.423 --> 21:01.259
MAKING THIS THE WORLD'S FIRST
TRULY SELF-SUFFICIENT SUB,

21:01.261 --> 21:05.296
CEMENTING PERAL'S CONTRIBUTION
TO MARINE POWER.

21:14.907 --> 21:18.242
♪

21:18.244 --> 21:20.278
[ CLOCK TICKING ]

21:21.948 --> 21:25.449
♪

21:25.451 --> 21:27.151
THE PERAL'S BATTERIES ALLOWED IT

21:27.153 --> 21:29.520
TO CRUISE UNDERWATER
FOR A FEW HOURS

21:29.522 --> 21:33.024
WITH A RANGE
OF 132 NAUTICAL MILES,

21:33.026 --> 21:35.860
BUT THE FORD CLASS' POWER SOURCE
CAN KEEP IT AT SEA

21:35.862 --> 21:39.664
FOR MONTHS AT A TIME
WITHOUT REFUELING.

21:39.666 --> 21:42.300
BUILDING ON MODERN
SUBMARINE TECHNOLOGY,

21:42.302 --> 21:43.668
THE SOLUTION IS A PAIR

21:43.670 --> 21:47.505
OF STATE-OF-THE-ART
NUCLEAR REACTORS.

21:47.507 --> 21:49.073
Stoecklein: ONE OF
THE MAJOR ADVANTAGES

21:49.075 --> 21:50.975
TO HAVING NUCLEAR POWER
IS AN ENGINEERING FEAT

21:50.977 --> 21:54.912
OF ACTUALLY GETTING 100,000 TONS
OF DISPLACEMENT

21:54.914 --> 21:56.614
WITH THE AIRCRAFT CARRIER
THROUGH THE WATER

21:56.616 --> 21:58.149
AT ABOUT 35-PLUS KNOTS.

21:58.151 --> 22:02.386
WE ARE ABLE TO HAVE 4.5 ACRES
OF SOVEREIGN AMERICAN SOIL

22:02.388 --> 22:04.155
ANYWHERE IN THE WORLD
FOR UP TO 25 YEARS

22:04.157 --> 22:05.990
AT A TIME UNDER NUCLEAR POWER.

22:08.695 --> 22:12.163
Narrator:
THE NUCLEAR REACTOR SPLIT
URANIUM, PRODUCING HEAT,

22:12.165 --> 22:16.734
WHICH CONVERTS WATER TO STEAM,
POWERING FOUR TURBINES.

22:16.736 --> 22:19.503
THESE ROTATE FOUR PROPELLER
SHAFTS TO DRIVE

22:19.505 --> 22:21.939
THE 1,100-FOOT-LONG CARRIER.

22:24.410 --> 22:26.677
BUT THE REACTOR'S OUTPUT
IS SO IMMENSE

22:26.679 --> 22:30.381
THEY CAN ALSO PRODUCE
HUGE AMOUNTS OF ELECTRICITY.

22:30.383 --> 22:32.483
UNLIKE ANY CARRIER BEFORE IT,

22:32.485 --> 22:35.319
VIRTUALLY EVERYTHING
ON THE TRAILBLAZING FORD CLASS

22:35.321 --> 22:37.855
IS POWERED BY ELECTRICITY.

22:37.857 --> 22:39.690
Stoecklein:<i> USS GERALD R. FORD</i>
CARRIES A LOAD

22:39.692 --> 22:42.993
OF 13.8 THOUSAND KILOVOLTS
OF AMPERAGE.

22:42.995 --> 22:45.796
SO YOU'RE LOOKING AT THREE TIMES
THE AMOUNT OF ELECTRICAL LOAD

22:45.798 --> 22:48.232
THAT THE AIRCRAFT CARRIERS
BEFORE US HAVE EVER HAD,

22:48.234 --> 22:50.301
AND THAT ALLOWS US
FOR SOME OF THE NEW TECHNOLOGY

22:50.303 --> 22:52.036
THAT WE HAVE ON BOARD.

22:54.073 --> 22:57.508
Narrator:
AND OVER 9.8 MILLION FEET
OF ELECTRICAL CABLING

22:57.510 --> 23:01.612
ALSO PROVIDE ENERGY
FOR THE 4,500 CREW ON BOARD.

23:01.614 --> 23:03.781
Stoecklein:
THE<i> USS GERALD R. FORD</i>
IS A FLOATING CITY,

23:03.783 --> 23:06.283
SO WE HAVE EVERY SERVICE
THAT A CIVILIAN COUNTERPART

23:06.285 --> 23:08.753
OR AN ACTUAL TOWNSHIP THAT
YOU MIGHT LIVE IN MIGHT HAVE.

23:08.755 --> 23:10.721
WE HAVE A POST OFFICE,
WE HAVE GYMS,

23:10.723 --> 23:13.991
WE HAVE A COFFEE SHOP,
WE HAVE LAUNDRY SERVICE.

23:13.993 --> 23:16.861
WE HAVE THAT ON BOARD SO THAT
WE CAN SUSTAIN OURSELVES OUT

23:16.863 --> 23:19.964
FOR LONG PERIODS OF TIME
AND REALLY BE EFFECTIVE.

23:22.969 --> 23:26.704
Narrator:
BUT THE CIVILIAN SERVICES ARE
NOT THE SHIP'S MAIN ATTRACTION.

23:26.706 --> 23:29.874
IT IS, AFTER ALL, A WARSHIP.

23:29.876 --> 23:34.412
THIS BRAND-NEW CARRIER CLASS
HAS 17 DECKS.

23:34.414 --> 23:39.383
ITS COLOSSAL FLIGHT DECK
STRETCHES TO FIVE ACRES.

23:39.385 --> 23:41.619
IT BOASTS SUPERSIZED ENGINEERING

23:41.621 --> 23:44.054
DESIGNED TO DEPLOY MORE
AIRCRAFT MISSIONS

23:44.056 --> 23:47.157
THAN EVER BEFORE
IN ANY PART OF THE WORLD.

23:47.159 --> 23:49.293
THE FIRST OF THIS GAME-CHANGING
FLEET

23:49.295 --> 23:52.997
HAS ONLY RECENTLY BEEN
COMMISSIONED INTO THE US NAVY.

23:52.999 --> 23:55.566
<i> USS GERALD R. FORD</i> IS SETTING
THE STANDARD AND SETTING THE BAR

23:55.568 --> 23:57.435
ON THE WAY THAT AIRCRAFT
CARRIERS AROUND THE WORLD

23:57.437 --> 23:58.936
AND THE WAY THAT NAVAL
OPERATIONS ARE GONNA BE

23:58.938 --> 24:01.639
DEALT WITH AND SUSTAINED.

24:01.641 --> 24:03.441
Narrator:
10 RECORD-BREAKING CARRIERS

24:03.443 --> 24:07.144
WILL EVENTUALLY MAKE UP
THE FORD CLASS.

24:07.146 --> 24:09.213
THE SECOND OF WHICH,
THE<i> JOHN F. KENNEDY,</i>

24:09.215 --> 24:11.615
IS CURRENTLY BEING ASSEMBLED.

24:11.617 --> 24:16.420
WHEN COMPLETED, IT WILL BE
WELL OVER 950 FEET LONG,

24:16.422 --> 24:18.088
BUT ITS RUNWAY WILL ONLY BE

24:18.090 --> 24:22.960
AROUND 1/7
OF A NORMAL RUNWAY'S LENGTH.

24:22.962 --> 24:24.995
LAUNCHING
AIRCRAFT IN THIS DISTANCE

24:24.997 --> 24:29.266
POSES A HUGE PROBLEM
FOR ENGINEER GABE SAVA.

24:29.268 --> 24:34.705
Sava:
THE RUNWAY ON THIS CARRIER
IS GONNA BE JUST UNDER 350 FEET.

24:34.707 --> 24:36.073
SO THE GREATEST CHALLENGE

24:36.075 --> 24:39.443
INVOLVED IN LAUNCHING
AN AIRCRAFT FROM A CARRIER

24:39.445 --> 24:42.880
IS THAT YOU ONLY HAVE
A FRACTION OF THE RUNWAY

24:42.882 --> 24:47.451
THAT AN AIRCRAFT TYPICALLY
WOULD NEED IN ORDER TO TAKE OFF.

24:47.453 --> 24:50.821
TO GET THE AIRCRAFT
TO THE ADEQUATE SPEED,

24:50.823 --> 24:53.858
WE HAVE TO USE
A SYSTEM OF LAUNCHING,

24:53.860 --> 24:56.794
WHICH IS A CATAPULT SYSTEM
THAT PROPELS

24:56.796 --> 25:02.233
AND ACCELERATES THE AIRCRAFT
SO THAT IT CAN TAKE OFF.

25:02.235 --> 25:05.569
Narrator:
TO DATE, LAUNCH CATAPULTS
HAVE BEEN STEAM-DRIVEN,

25:05.571 --> 25:08.072
BUT THESE SYSTEMS
LACK ACCELERATION CONTROL

25:08.074 --> 25:11.075
AND WOULD RIP APART
THE FORD CLASS' LIGHTER AIRCRAFT

25:11.077 --> 25:14.445
SUCH AS UNMANNED DRONES.

25:14.447 --> 25:18.215
Sava:
STEAM-POWERED CATAPULTS,
BY THEIR VERY NATURE,

25:18.217 --> 25:22.419
CAN PUT A LOT OF LOADS
OR STRESS ON THE AIRCRAFT.

25:22.421 --> 25:26.357
IN ADDITION, STEAM CATAPULTS
REQUIRE A LOT OF MAINTENANCE.

25:26.359 --> 25:29.260
THERE'S A LOT OF CORROSION
WITHIN THE TROUGHS

25:29.262 --> 25:32.329
BECAUSE THERE'S
A LOT OF MOISTURE.

25:32.331 --> 25:35.633
Narrator:
ENGINEERS NEEDED A WAY
TO GET AIRCRAFT UP TO SPEED

25:35.635 --> 25:38.736
WHILE ALSO PROTECTING
THEIR STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY

25:38.738 --> 25:42.973
AND THAT OF
THE LAUNCHING APPARATUS.

25:42.975 --> 25:44.975
TO DO SO,
THEY WOULD HAVE TO TURN

25:44.977 --> 25:47.077
TO THE INNOVATORS OF THE PAST.

25:58.858 --> 26:04.461
♪

26:04.463 --> 26:07.765
Narrator: ON THE U.S. NAVY'S
MOST ADVANCED WARSHIP EVER,

26:07.767 --> 26:09.133
TRADITIONAL SHIP-TO-AIR

26:09.135 --> 26:11.535
LAUNCH TECHNIQUES
WEREN'T GOING TO CUT IT.

26:14.073 --> 26:16.407
THE TEAM BEHIND THIS
MONSTER VESSEL

26:16.409 --> 26:19.143
NEEDED A WAY TO GET AIRCRAFT UP
TO LAUNCH SPEED

26:19.145 --> 26:22.313
WITH ABOUT 1/7
OF THE TRADITIONAL RUNWAY.

26:26.152 --> 26:27.618
THE FORD CLASS' ENGINEERS

26:27.620 --> 26:30.054
PROPOSED
A GROUNDBREAKING SOLUTION --

26:30.056 --> 26:33.524
CATAPULT POWER GENERATED
BY ELECTROMAGNETICS.

26:36.162 --> 26:39.363
PETTY OFFICER DANIEL RIVERA
IS PART OF THE LAUNCH TEAM

26:39.365 --> 26:42.967
INVOLVED IN THE INITIAL TESTING.

26:42.969 --> 26:45.102
Rivera: WE HAVE TO PERFORM
WHAT'S CALLED DEAD-LOAD TESTING.

26:45.104 --> 26:48.405
A DEAD LOAD IS, ESSENTIALLY,
A BIG PIECE OF METAL ON WHEELS

26:48.407 --> 26:51.008
THAT REPRESENTS
DIFFERENT AIRCRAFT WEIGHTS.

26:51.010 --> 26:53.243
AND PRETTY MUCH,
WE WERE ON THE FLIGHT DECK,

26:53.245 --> 26:54.945
AND WE LAUNCH EACH DEAD LOAD.

26:54.947 --> 26:57.348
THE DEAD LOADS WILL GO
ACTUALLY OFF THE BOAT.

26:57.350 --> 27:00.284
THEY WILL TAKE OFF AND FLY
OVER INTO THE JAMES RIVER.

27:00.286 --> 27:08.225
♪

27:08.227 --> 27:10.995
Narrator:
CONCEALED BELOW THE CATAPULT'S
SHUTTLE AND RAILS,

27:10.997 --> 27:13.430
THE ELECTROMAGNETIC
AIRCRAFT-LAUNCH SYSTEM,

27:13.432 --> 27:14.999
KNOWN AS EMALS,

27:15.001 --> 27:18.902
USES THE SHIP'S POWER TO CREATE
AN ENORMOUS ELECTRICAL CHARGE.

27:24.010 --> 27:27.244
Rivera:
THE SYSTEM USES 13,800 KILOVOLTS

27:27.246 --> 27:28.679
THAT'S BEING GENERATED
FROM THE SHIP

27:28.681 --> 27:30.481
IN ORDER TO POWER THE EQUIPMENT,

27:30.483 --> 27:33.984
AND WITH THAT ENERGY, WE'RE ABLE
TO LAUNCH AN AIRCRAFT ZERO

27:33.986 --> 27:38.022
TO ABOUT 150 MILES PER HOUR
IN JUST UNDER 3 SECONDS.

27:42.895 --> 27:47.231
Narrator:
WITH THE PLANE ON 100% THROTTLE,
THIS HUGE SHOT OF ELECTRICITY

27:47.233 --> 27:49.933
IS RELEASED INTO A SERIES
OF ELECTROMAGNETS

27:49.935 --> 27:52.469
POSITIONED DOWN
TWO LAUNCH RAILS.

27:52.471 --> 27:54.605
A POWERFUL MAGNETIC WAVE PROPELS

27:54.607 --> 27:56.907
THE ATTACHED PLANE
OFF THE RUNWAY.

27:59.645 --> 28:02.579
WITH EMALS, THE POWER THAT WE
PRODUCE DURING EACH AIRCRAFT

28:02.581 --> 28:04.481
LAUNCH IS A LOT MORE CONTROLLED.

28:04.483 --> 28:05.916
SO, FOR THAT REASON,

28:05.918 --> 28:08.152
WE CAN BE ABLE TO LAUNCH
A WIDER RANGE OF AIRCRAFT.

28:08.154 --> 28:09.753
USING COMPUTER SOFTWARE

28:09.755 --> 28:11.822
WHILE THE CATAPULT
IS GOING DOWN THE TRACK,

28:11.824 --> 28:13.691
IT KNOWS HOW MUCH POWER
IS NEEDED

28:13.693 --> 28:15.859
IN ORDER TO GET THAT AIRCRAFT
OFF THE DECK.

28:18.164 --> 28:20.998
Narrator:
BUT SOMETIMES EVEN THE MIGHTY
EMALS CATAPULT

28:21.000 --> 28:25.235
ISN'T ENOUGH TO GET
THE JETS OFF THE DECK.

28:25.237 --> 28:28.405
CHIEF PETTY OFFICER JEREMY
STOECKLEIN HAS EXPERIENCED

28:28.407 --> 28:32.743
THIS POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS
SITUATION FIRSTHAND.

28:32.745 --> 28:34.311
Stoecklein:
THERE ARE TIMES THAT WE'RE OUT
IN THE MIDDLE OF THE OCEAN,

28:34.313 --> 28:36.146
DEPENDING ON WEATHER,
DEPENDING ON WHAT THE AIRCRAFT

28:36.148 --> 28:37.648
NEEDS TO BE LOADED DOWN WITH,

28:37.650 --> 28:40.417
SOMETIMES THAT AIRCRAFT
DOESN'T HAVE ENOUGH POWER

28:40.419 --> 28:43.153
ON 100% THROTTLE
TO REACH THAT MINIMUM AIR SPEED,

28:43.155 --> 28:45.689
AND SOMETIMES WE NEED
JUST A LITTLE BIT EXTRA.

28:45.691 --> 28:47.057
Narrator: FOR THE ENGINEERS,

28:47.059 --> 28:50.627
THIS IS A PROBLEM
THAT COULD END IN DISASTER.

28:50.629 --> 28:52.296
Rivera: IF THE AIRCRAFT
DIDN'T HAVE ENOUGH POWER,

28:52.298 --> 28:53.731
IT COULD BE VERY CATASTROPHIC,

28:53.733 --> 28:55.399
BECAUSE THE AIRCRAFT COULD END
UP GOING INTO THE WATER

28:55.401 --> 28:57.434
AND NOT TAKING OFF AT ALL.

28:57.436 --> 29:01.405
Narrator:
SO HOW CAN THESE PHENOMENAL
GETS PRODUCE MORE POWER?

29:01.407 --> 29:04.274
IT'S A CHALLENGE THAT'S BEEN
FACED IN THE PAST.

29:07.179 --> 29:10.481
[ TICKING ]

29:10.483 --> 29:15.619
♪

29:15.621 --> 29:18.288
ENGINEER DAN DICKRELL IS
AT THE PATUXENT RIVER

29:18.290 --> 29:20.057
NAVAL AIR BASE IN MARYLAND,

29:20.059 --> 29:22.359
THE SITE OF
AN EXTRAORDINARY INNOVATION

29:22.361 --> 29:25.562
THAT COULD PROVIDE A SOLUTION
FOR THE FORD CLASS.

29:28.601 --> 29:30.200
Dickrell:
THIS IS A T-38 TALON.

29:30.202 --> 29:32.136
IT'S A TWO-SEAT TRAINER.

29:32.138 --> 29:35.739
IT'S POWERED BY TWO
GENERAL ELECTRIC J85 ENGINES.

29:35.741 --> 29:38.208
TOP SPEED'S OVER
1,200 MILES PER HOUR,

29:38.210 --> 29:41.645
WHICH IS SUPERSONIC,
FASTER THAN THE SPEED OF SOUND.

29:41.647 --> 29:44.848
Narrator:
TODAY, THE T-38 IS ENTERING
THE HUSH HOUSE,

29:44.850 --> 29:47.851
A SECRETIVE TEST FACILITY
WHERE ENGINEERS CAN SEE

29:47.853 --> 29:51.855
HOW JET ENGINES
PERFORM UP CLOSE.

29:51.857 --> 29:54.625
Dickrell: ALL RIGHT,
SO THE T-38's TIED DOWN.

29:54.627 --> 29:56.426
THE TEST IS ABOUT TO BEGIN.

29:56.428 --> 29:58.162
LET'S DO IT.

30:00.299 --> 30:03.467
Narrator: WITH SPECIAL CLEARANCE
JUST FEET FROM THE ENGINE,

30:03.469 --> 30:06.470
DAN IS WITNESSING A TEST
THAT WILL REVEAL ONE OF THE KEYS

30:06.472 --> 30:10.207
TO A SUCCESSFUL
AIRCRAFT-CARRIER LAUNCH.

30:10.209 --> 30:12.776
HERE WE GO.
TEST IS BEGINNING.

30:12.778 --> 30:15.078
[ ENGINE REVVING ]
PRETTY EXCITED.

30:15.080 --> 30:16.480
YOU CAN HEAR IT FUELING UP.

30:24.657 --> 30:26.456
[ FUEL IGNITES ]

30:40.239 --> 30:42.139
Narrator:
THIS INCREDIBLE SIGHT IS CREATED

30:42.141 --> 30:44.675
BY WHAT'S KNOWN
AS AN AFTERBURNER.

30:48.714 --> 30:51.281
IT'S THE SECRET TO PRODUCING
THE THRUST REQUIRED

30:51.283 --> 30:53.250
BY THE FORD CLASS' JETS.

30:53.252 --> 30:59.189
♪

30:59.191 --> 31:03.160
IT WAS INVENTED OVER 85 YEARS
AGO BY SIR FRANK WHITTLE,

31:03.162 --> 31:05.896
ONE OF THE FOREFATHERS
OF THE AIRCRAFT ENGINE.

31:08.601 --> 31:11.134
Reporter:
A METEOR JET PLANE IS READY
FOR AN UNOFFICIAL APPROACH

31:11.136 --> 31:13.036
TO THE SOUND BARRIER.

31:13.038 --> 31:15.439
Narrator: DURING THE 1940s,
THE RACE WAS ON,

31:15.441 --> 31:17.608
NOT ONLY TO BREAK
THE SOUND BARRIER,

31:17.610 --> 31:20.911
BUT ALSO TO REACH
1,000 MILES PER HOUR.

31:20.913 --> 31:22.880
JET ENGINES NEEDED MORE POWER,

31:22.882 --> 31:25.415
BUT MAKING THEM BIGGER
WAS OUT OF THE QUESTION.

31:25.417 --> 31:29.419
SO WHITTLE DEVISED HIS RADICAL
SOLUTION, THE AFTERBURNER.

31:29.421 --> 31:31.755
SEE, IT'S RIGHT HERE ON THE BACK
OF THE ENGINE.

31:31.757 --> 31:33.724
IT VASTLY INCREASES THE AMOUNT
OF THRUST

31:33.726 --> 31:35.225
THAT'S AVAILABLE TO THE ENGINE

31:35.227 --> 31:39.329
WITHOUT ADDING MUCH WEIGHT OR
COMPLEXITY TO THE ENGINE ITSELF.

31:39.331 --> 31:42.466
Narrator:
WITH MINIMAL ADJUSTMENTS,
WHITTLE FIGURED OUT HOW TO

31:42.468 --> 31:45.869
DRAMATICALLY OUTPERFORM
THE STANDARD JET ENGINE,

31:45.871 --> 31:49.172
AND HIS INGENIOUS MODIFICATION
HOLDS THE KEY

31:49.174 --> 31:51.008
TO GETTING AIRCRAFT
FROM THE DECK

31:51.010 --> 31:54.378
OF A FORD-CLASS
AIRCRAFT CARRIER TO THE SKIES.

32:06.358 --> 32:11.929
♪

32:11.931 --> 32:15.198
Narrator: WHEN ENGINEERS BEHIND
THE FORD-CLASS AIRCRAFT CARRIER

32:15.200 --> 32:17.634
NEEDED TO GET AIRCRAFT
FROM DECK TO AIR

32:17.636 --> 32:20.370
USING ABOUT 1/7
OF THE RUNWAY SPACE,

32:20.372 --> 32:23.674
THE ANSWER WAS THRUST,
AND THEY TURNED TO SIR FRANK

32:23.676 --> 32:29.413
WHITTLE'S HISTORIC INNOVATION
TO PROVIDE IT.

32:29.415 --> 32:32.683
A STANDARD JET ENGINE
TAKES AIR IN, ADDS FUEL,

32:32.685 --> 32:36.553
AND IGNITES THE MIXTURE,
PROPELLING THE AIRCRAFT FORWARD.

32:36.555 --> 32:39.489
WHITTLE REALIZED MUCH OF
THE OXYGEN WAS UNUSED,

32:39.491 --> 32:42.192
SO HE ADDED MORE FUEL
AT THE REAR OF THE ENGINE

32:42.194 --> 32:45.429
TO UTILIZE IT.

32:45.431 --> 32:49.599
THIS CREATES A MASSIVE AMOUNT
OF EXTRA THRUST.

32:49.601 --> 32:51.001
Dickrell:
WHEN YOU'RE DESIGNING SOMETHING,

32:51.003 --> 32:52.836
THE SIMPLER IS
USUALLY THE BETTER,

32:52.838 --> 32:55.572
AND WHITTLE'S SOLUTION
IS AMAZINGLY SIMPLE

32:55.574 --> 32:58.342
YET ITS PERFORMANCE
INCREASE IS BRILLIANT.

33:02.281 --> 33:05.048
Narrator: TO FULLY APPRECIATE
THE AFTERBURN EXPERIENCE,

33:05.050 --> 33:07.150
AND AIR-FORCE VETERAN,
BUD GREEN,

33:07.152 --> 33:11.154
IS REACQUAINTING HIMSELF
WITH THE F-100,

33:11.156 --> 33:15.692
THE FIRST US JET
TO FLY SUPERSONIC.

33:15.694 --> 33:19.329
ZERO TO 62 MILES PER HOUR
TAKES JUST SECONDS.

33:21.633 --> 33:25.202
Green: OH.

33:25.204 --> 33:28.839
Narrator:
AT TOP SPEED, IT SMASHES
THROUGH THE SOUND BARRIER.

33:33.178 --> 33:36.079
COURTESY OF A STAGGERING
PIECE OF ENGINEERING.

33:44.256 --> 33:45.922
[ LAUGHS ]

33:49.161 --> 33:51.228
WE WERE GOING ABOUT
320 OR SOMETHING LIKE
THAT WHEN HE LIT IT,

33:51.230 --> 33:53.897
AND YOU CAN REALLY
FEEL THE KICK.

33:53.899 --> 33:55.999
JUST, ALL OF A SUDDEN,
YOU'VE GOT A WHOLE BUNCH

33:56.001 --> 33:57.734
OF ADDITIONAL THRUST,

33:57.736 --> 33:59.603
AND IT JUST KNOCKS YOU
ON THE REAR END.

33:59.605 --> 34:00.704
IT WAS FUN.

34:00.706 --> 34:02.005
DOES REALLY KICK.

34:02.007 --> 34:03.740
UNBELIEVABLE.

34:05.978 --> 34:08.612
[ TICKING ]

34:11.617 --> 34:14.384
Narrator:
WHITTLE'S AFTERBURNER CONCEPT
CHANGED THE GAME

34:14.386 --> 34:18.221
FOR FORD CLASS' JETS.

34:18.223 --> 34:20.590
Stoecklein:
THE ABILITY OF THE AIRCRAFT
TO HAVE THIS AFTERBURNER OPTION

34:20.592 --> 34:22.125
INCREASES OUR FLEXIBILITY

34:22.127 --> 34:25.195
AND ALLOWS US TO GO UP IN WEIGHT
WITH THAT EXTRA BOOST OF ENERGY

34:25.197 --> 34:26.997
THAT WILL ALLOW US TO REACH
THAT MINIMUM AIR SPEED

34:26.999 --> 34:29.499
SO WE CAN CARRY
MORE ORDINANCE, MORE FUEL,

34:29.501 --> 34:31.802
ANYTHING THAT WE NEED
TO COMPLETE OUR MISSION.

34:31.804 --> 34:37.307
♪

34:37.309 --> 34:39.443
Narrator:
LAUNCHING OVER 200 JETS A DAY

34:39.445 --> 34:41.778
IS AN INCREDIBLE FEAT
OF ENGINEERING,

34:41.780 --> 34:44.881
BUT IT'S ONLY
HALF THE STORY.

34:44.883 --> 34:47.417
BRINGING THEM HOME
IS EVEN HARDER.

34:49.455 --> 34:51.154
Sava: LANDING AN AIRCRAFT
IS DEFINITELY

34:51.156 --> 34:53.356
ONE OF THE MOST
DANGEROUS ACTIVITIES

34:53.358 --> 34:56.259
THAT YOU DO
ON THE FLIGHT DECK.

34:56.261 --> 34:58.028
Narrator: SOMEHOW,
THE JETS HAVE TO STOP

34:58.030 --> 35:00.864
IN JUST 1/7
OF A NORMAL RUNWAY'S LENGTH

35:00.866 --> 35:04.034
OR THEY'LL END UP
IN THE WATER.

35:04.036 --> 35:07.270
CAN A BOLD PIONEER
FROM THE PAST PROVIDE A SOLUTION

35:07.272 --> 35:10.140
TO THIS SEEMINGLY
IMPOSSIBLE CHALLENGE?

35:13.011 --> 35:16.279
[ TICKING ]

35:16.281 --> 35:21.351
♪

35:21.353 --> 35:22.819
IT MAY BE HARD TO BELIEVE,

35:22.821 --> 35:25.622
BUT THIS BEAUTIFUL BIPLANE
COULD HOLD THE KEY

35:25.624 --> 35:27.924
TO LANDING
ON THE FORD-CLASS CARRIERS.

35:27.926 --> 35:31.361
[ PROPELLER HUMS ]

35:31.363 --> 35:35.065
ENGINEER DAN DICKRELL
IS IN VIRGINIA, DISCOVERING HOW.

35:38.504 --> 35:41.404
SO, THAT MOTORLESS AIRPLANE
THAT JUST TOOK OFF

35:41.406 --> 35:43.273
IS THE ELY CURTISS PUSHER.

35:43.275 --> 35:46.443
EVEN THOUGH THAT'S A REPLICA,
IT WAS BUILT IN 1910,

35:46.445 --> 35:50.380
AND IT FIRST FLEW IN 1911.

35:50.382 --> 35:52.282
Narrator:
THE CURTISS PUSHER IS UNIQUE

35:52.284 --> 35:55.952
BECAUSE IT WAS THE FIRST PLANE
TO TAKE OFF FROM A WARSHIP,

35:55.954 --> 35:59.556
BUT AMERICAN EUGENE ELY
WASN'T SATISFIED.

35:59.558 --> 36:02.592
HE ALSO WANTED TO LAND
HIS PLANE ON A SHIP.

36:04.696 --> 36:10.300
HOWEVER, HE ONLY HAD
120 FEET TO WORK WITH,

36:10.302 --> 36:15.238
A PROBLEM DEMONSTRATED AS
TODAY'S FLIGHT DRAWS TO A CLOSE.

36:15.240 --> 36:16.606
Dickrell:
WHEN THE BIPLANE LANDED,

36:16.608 --> 36:18.608
IT FIRST TOUCHED DOWN
RIGHT ABOUT HERE,

36:18.610 --> 36:20.110
AND IT COASTED TO A STOP.

36:20.112 --> 36:22.112
I'M GONNA PACE IT OFF AND SEE
HOW FAR IT TOOK

36:22.114 --> 36:24.147
TO COME TO A COMPLETE STOP.

36:25.317 --> 36:27.884
Narrator: IF THIS PLANE WAS
LANDING ON ELY'S SHIP,

36:27.886 --> 36:33.857
ANYTHING OVER 120 FEET
WOULD'VE ENDED IN DISASTER.

36:33.859 --> 36:35.625
ALL RIGHT, HERE.
HEY, BOOM, HOW'S IT GOING?

36:35.627 --> 36:37.360
-HOW YOU DOING?
-TERRIFIC. HOW MUCH WAS IT?

36:37.362 --> 36:39.596
IT WAS 275 FEET.

36:39.598 --> 36:41.064
UGH.
IT WOULD'VE SMACKED PROBABLY

36:41.066 --> 36:43.567
RIGHT INTO THE SUPERSTRUCTURE
OF THE SHIP IN THAT CASE,

36:43.569 --> 36:46.102
OR OVER THE SIDE IF THERE
WASN'T A SUPERSTRUCTURE.

36:48.740 --> 36:51.942
Narrator:
BUT ELY HAD THE HELP OF ENGINEER
HUGH ROBINSON,

36:51.944 --> 36:54.511
WHO CAME UP WITH AN IDEA
TO BRING HIS AIRCRAFT

36:54.513 --> 36:56.112
SAFELY TO A HALT.

36:56.114 --> 37:00.483
IT'S A SOLUTION THAT COULD HELP
THE FORD CLASS.

37:00.485 --> 37:02.586
ROBINSON CAME UP
WITH ARRESTING GEAR.

37:02.588 --> 37:04.054
THIS WAS A SYSTEM
THAT WAS DESIGNED

37:04.056 --> 37:05.755
TO BRING THE PLANE TO A STOP.

37:05.757 --> 37:09.492
IT WAS A LITTLE MORE
THAN ROPE AND SANDBAGS.

37:09.494 --> 37:12.162
Narrator:
ROBINSON TIED THE ROPE
BETWEEN THE SANDBAGS

37:12.164 --> 37:14.064
ACROSS THE SHIP'S DECK.

37:14.066 --> 37:17.000
THE PLAN WAS TO TRANSFER
THE LANDING PLANE'S MOMENTUM

37:17.002 --> 37:19.936
INTO THE HEAVY BAGS
BY ADDING A TAILHOOK

37:19.938 --> 37:23.039
THAT WOULD SNAG THE ROPE
AS THE PLANE PASSED OVER IT.

37:26.678 --> 37:29.913
AND IN 1911, THIS SIMPLE
SOLUTION BROUGHT

37:29.915 --> 37:33.750
ELY'S PLANE SAFELY
TO A STANDSTILL IN JUST 30 FEET

37:33.752 --> 37:35.885
ON BOARD
THE CONVERTED WARSHIP.

37:38.323 --> 37:40.690
THAT PARTICULAR INNOVATION
WAS THE EXAMPLE

37:40.692 --> 37:44.194
THAT LANDING AIRCRAFT
ON SHIPS WAS POSSIBLE.

37:44.196 --> 37:46.529
IT REALLY PAVED THE WAY
FOR WHAT WE SEE TODAY.

37:49.935 --> 37:52.669
[ TICKING ]

37:53.639 --> 37:58.675
♪

37:58.677 --> 38:00.677
Narrator:
NOW THE FORD CLASS' ENGINEERS

38:00.679 --> 38:03.980
ARE ADAPTING ROBINSON'S
INGENIOUS CONCEPT.

38:06.018 --> 38:10.887
BUT AT 65 TIMES HEAVIER
AND 4 TIMES FASTER,

38:10.889 --> 38:14.457
THEIR JETS WILL REQUIRE
MORE THAN ROPE AND SANDBAGS.

38:14.459 --> 38:19.562
♪

38:19.564 --> 38:22.766
THE TEAM BEHIND THE FORD CLASS
WILL HAVE TO SUPERSIZE

38:22.768 --> 38:25.535
THE INNOVATIVE
CONCEPT OF ARRESTING GEAR

38:25.537 --> 38:27.637
TO BRING
THE CARRIER'S NAVY AIRCRAFT

38:27.639 --> 38:33.677
SAFELY BACK DOWN TO EARTH.

38:42.020 --> 38:47.390
♪

38:47.392 --> 38:49.592
Narrator: WITH LITTLE
DECK SPACE TO LAND ON,

38:49.594 --> 38:53.229
THE ENGINEERS DESIGNING
THE FORD-CLASS AIRCRAFT CARRIER

38:53.231 --> 38:57.167
NEEDED A WAY TO STOP DESCENDING
AIRCRAFT IN THEIR TRACKS.

38:59.938 --> 39:02.372
THE SOLUTION IS
A CUTTING-EDGE SYSTEM

39:02.374 --> 39:06.509
KNOWN AS
ADVANCED ARRESTING GEAR.

39:06.511 --> 39:09.179
Sava: THE CURRENT
ADVANCED-ARRESTING-GEAR SYSTEM

39:09.181 --> 39:13.717
ON THE FORD CAN ARREST AIRCRAFT
UP TO 50,000 POUNDS.

39:13.719 --> 39:17.420
IN ORDER TO DO THIS,
IT HAS TO HAVE PRECISE CONTROLS

39:17.422 --> 39:20.323
SO THAT YOU DON'T OVERSTRESS
THE AIRCRAFT.

39:20.325 --> 39:22.092
AS THE AIRCRAFT APPROACHES,

39:22.094 --> 39:26.329
IT PICKS UP THE PENDANT
OFF THE DECK.

39:26.331 --> 39:31.701
THE CABLE TENSION THEN GOES
THROUGH A CABLE SHOCK ABSORBER.

39:31.703 --> 39:36.339
THE SHOCK ABSORBER TAKES OUT
THE WAVE IN THE CABLE.

39:36.341 --> 39:39.109
IT'S KIND OF LIKE CAR SHOCKS.

39:39.111 --> 39:44.180
THEN THE BRAKING POWER
IS PROVIDED BY A WATER TWISTER.

39:48.019 --> 39:49.919
Narrator: SITUATED BELOW DECK,

39:49.921 --> 39:53.823
THE WATER TWISTER IS A PADDLE
WHEEL SUBMERGED IN FLUID.

39:53.825 --> 39:56.526
ITS ROTATION PROVIDES
FRICTIONAL RESISTANCE,

39:56.528 --> 40:01.698
ABSORBING AROUND 2/3
OF THE LANDING'S ENERGY.

40:01.700 --> 40:07.203
Sava:
THE REMAINDER OF THE ARRESTMENT
IS CONTROLLED PRECISELY

40:07.205 --> 40:11.508
BY A MOTOR GENERATOR
THAT TAKES THAT KINETIC ENERGY

40:11.510 --> 40:14.310
AND TURNS IT INTO
ELECTRICAL ENERGY

40:14.312 --> 40:21.484
THAT IS THEN STORED
FOR LATER USES ON AAG.

40:21.486 --> 40:25.422
Narrator:
THE ADVANCED ARRESTING GEAR
IS ALSO INCREDIBLY ADAPTABLE.

40:25.424 --> 40:29.259
DURING A TWO-SECOND LANDING,
COMPUTER CONTROLS CONTINUALLY

40:29.261 --> 40:32.629
ADJUST THE GEAR ACCORDING
TO THE AIRCRAFT'S WEIGHT.

40:32.631 --> 40:35.732
IN OTHER WORDS,
I CAN ARREST LIGHTER AIRCRAFT

40:35.734 --> 40:38.635
THAN I WOULD'VE BEEN ABLE TO
WITH MY OLD SYSTEM

40:38.637 --> 40:40.336
OR HEAVIER AIRCRAFT

40:40.338 --> 40:45.008
BECAUSE I HAVE THE ABILITY TO
ACTIVELY CONTROL THE ARRESTMENT.

40:45.010 --> 40:50.447
THIS SYSTEM ALSO ACTIVELY
COMPENSATES FOR THE AIRCRAFT

40:50.449 --> 40:54.551
BEING POTENTIALLY OFF-CENTER
OR OFF-TARGET,

40:54.553 --> 40:59.289
AND IT IS ABLE TO CONTROL
THE PAYOUT OF CABLE

40:59.291 --> 41:03.193
IN ORDER TO REDUCE THE AMOUNT
OF STRESS ON THE AIRCRAFT

41:03.195 --> 41:05.762
AND LAND IT SAFELY.

41:05.764 --> 41:08.798
Narrator:
BRILLIANT ENGINEERING IS TAKING
ANOTHER OF HISTORY'S

41:08.800 --> 41:12.402
INSPIRED INNOVATIONS
INTO THE 21st CENTURY.

41:12.404 --> 41:20.477
♪

41:20.479 --> 41:24.314
FOR THOSE WHO SERVE ON BOARD,
THE FORD CLASS IS UNDOUBTEDLY

41:24.316 --> 41:27.917
TAKING AIRCRAFT-CARRIER DESIGN
TO NEW HEIGHTS.

41:32.757 --> 41:35.792
Stoecklein: THE FACT THAT
A 17-DECK, 4.5-ACRE,

41:35.794 --> 41:37.927
100,000-TON IN-WEIGHT SHIP

41:37.929 --> 41:42.198
CAN BE IN SERVICE FOR 50 YEARS
IS JUST AN INCREDIBLE THOUGHT.

41:42.200 --> 41:43.933
Narrator: THROUGH
THE EXTRAORDINARY EFFORTS

41:43.935 --> 41:46.169
OF ITS DESIGNERS AND CREW,

41:46.171 --> 41:50.907
THIS AMBITIOUS CLASS IS CHANGING
THE FACE OF MARINE ENGINEERING.

41:50.909 --> 41:53.476
Hummel:
FOR ME, IT'S A TREMENDOUS HONOR
TO BE PART OF THE TEAM

41:53.478 --> 41:58.014
COMING TOGETHER TO PUT TOGETHER
THIS GREAT NAVY SHIP.

41:58.016 --> 42:01.684
Narrator:
BY BUILDING ON THE WORK OF THE
PIONEERS OF THE PAST,

42:01.686 --> 42:06.756
UPSCALING, AND MAKING
THEIR OWN DISCOVERIES,

42:06.758 --> 42:08.791
THE ENGINEERS ARE SUCCEEDING

42:08.793 --> 42:12.695
IN MAKING THE IMPOSSIBLE
POSSIBLE.

42:12.697 --> 42:14.497
WHERE WE GO FROM HERE --
REALLY, THE SKY'S THE LIMIT,

42:14.499 --> 42:16.432
Stoecklein: AND I THINK
<i> USS GERALD R. FORD</i> SHOWS

42:16.434 --> 42:19.502
THAT IMPOSSIBLE ENGINEERING
IS NOT SO IMPOSSIBLE.
